  {
    question: 'Can I request an advance on my TFR while still employed?',
    answer: 'Yes, under Art. 2120 of the Civil Code, employees who have at least <strong>8 years of continuous service</strong> with the same employer may request an advance of up to <strong>70%</strong> of the TFR accrued to that date. The advance can only be requested once during the employment relationship (some CCNLs allow a second request) and must be justified by specific needs: (1) healthcare expenses for the employee or family members; (2) purchase of a primary residence for the employee or their children. The employer is obligated to grant the advance, but only up to 10% of eligible employees (and 4% of the total workforce) may receive it in any given year.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How is TFR taxed when I receive it?',
    answer: 'TFR is subject to <strong>tassazione separata</strong> (separate taxation), meaning it is not added to your regular annual income and does not push you into a higher IRPEF bracket. Instead, it is taxed at an average rate calculated on your income over the years the TFR accrued. The formula uses your average taxable income from the last 5 years, applies the IRPEF brackets to that average, and derives a percentage that is then applied to the TFR amount. For most employees, this results in a <strong>lower effective tax rate</strong> than the marginal IRPEF rate they pay on regular income. The annual revaluation portion of the TFR is taxed separately at a flat 17% substitute tax.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What happens to my TFR if my employer goes bankrupt?',
    answer: 'Your TFR is protected by the <strong>Fondo di Garanzia INPS</strong> (INPS Guarantee Fund), established by Legge 297/1982. If your employer becomes insolvent, enters bankruptcy proceedings (fallimento), or undergoes other insolvency procedures (concordato preventivo, liquidazione coatta amministrativa), the INPS Guarantee Fund steps in to pay your accumulated TFR in full. To claim it, you must file a request with INPS after the insolvency has been officially declared and the employer\'s debt to you has been verified by the court-appointed receiver (curatore fallimentare). The fund also covers the last three months of unpaid wages. Processing times vary, but typically range from 60 to 120 days after the claim is submitted. This guarantee applies regardless of the company size. For companies with more than 50 employees, the TFR is already held by INPS (Fondo di Tesoreria), further reducing the risk. See <a href="https://www.inps.it/it/it/dettaglio-scheda.schede-servizio-strumento.schede-servizi.fondo-di-garanzia-tfr-50054.fondo-di-garanzia-tfr.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">INPS &mdash; Fondo di Garanzia TFR</a> for details.',
